<BaseLayout
  title="Building Your Own MCP Server: Implementation Steps — AI Agent Puzzle"
  description="Turn the previous page's design into runnable code: create the project folder, install uv, write a minimal server.py, hook it up to Gemini CLI, add the full toolset, and run a complete reflection-draft flow. Each step ships with full commands and safety boundaries."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container ai-agent-impl">
      <a class="back-link" href="/learning/ai-agent/custom-server/concepts">&larr; Back to Concepts & Design</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Building Your Own MCP Server: Implementation Steps</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          On the previous page we sketched out the tool surface: four tools, one resource, one prompt. This page <strong>builds it</strong>. Each step ships with full commands. If a step doesn't pass, stop and fix it before moving on.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- ============ Part 1: Get a minimal version running ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 1</span>
        <span class="part-text">Get a Minimal Version Running</span>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 1 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 1</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Create a Project Folder in VS Code</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Create a folder somewhere convenient, named <code>my-first-mcp-server</code>. Then open VS Code and choose <strong>File → Open Folder</strong>, and pick the folder you just created.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Once it's open, create the following folders and files in the file explorer:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block code-block--tree" is:raw><code>my-first-mcp-server/
├─ server.py
├─ class_notes/
│  ├─ ai_agent_basics.md
│  └─ mcp_tools_resources_prompts.md
└─ drafts/</code></pre>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><code>server.py</code> — our MCP server program</li>
        <li><code>class_notes/</code> — holds the original class notes</li>
        <li><code>drafts/</code> — holds reflection drafts the AI creates</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          The point: <strong>scope what the AI can touch to this folder.</strong> Don't let it read your whole machine on day one, and don't point it at anything important right away.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 2 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 2</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Install the MCP Package</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Time to install the MCP Python SDK. Two options.
      </p>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">Option 1: Install with uv (recommended)</h3>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        With uv, first make sure VS Code has <code>my-first-mcp-server</code> open. Then in VS Code's integrated terminal, run:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">powershell -ExecutionPolicy ByPass -c "irm https://astral.sh/uv/install.ps1 | iex"
uv init</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The first command is uv's official Windows installer. The second <strong>initializes the current folder as a uv project</strong>.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">Then run:</p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">uv add "mcp[cli]"</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This adds the MCP packages to the project.
      </p>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Two reasons to use uv: (1) it keeps the project's environment together, so when Gemini CLI starts the MCP server it can do so via <code>uv run</code>; (2) it makes <strong>package and virtual-env management cleaner and more consistent</strong>, so different projects don't clobber each other.
        </p>
      </div>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Option 2: Install with pip</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            With pip, in VS Code's integrated terminal:
          </p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">python -m venv .venv</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            This creates a <code>.venv</code> virtual environment in the project. Then activate it.
          </p>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">On Windows PowerShell:</p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">On macOS or Linux:</p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">source .venv/bin/activate</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">Once activated, install MCP:</p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">python -m pip install "mcp[cli]"</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            What this means: <strong>use the current Python</strong> to run pip install. Avoid plain <code>pip install "mcp[cli]"</code> — sometimes there are multiple Pythons on a machine and bare <code>pip</code> may install into an environment you didn't expect.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          This guide <strong>uses Option 1</strong> because it teaches a useful habit: a dedicated virtual environment per project. Every step below assumes Option 1.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 3 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 3</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Write a Minimal MCP Server First</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Open <code>server.py</code> and drop this in:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">from mcp.server.fastmcp import FastMCP

mcp = FastMCP("Course Notes Assistant")


@mcp.tool()
def hello() -> str:
    """Confirm the class-notes MCP server is up."""
    return "Class-notes MCP server is running."


if __name__ == "__main__":
    mcp.run()</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This program has <strong>one tool</strong>, <code>hello</code>. It doesn't read files. It doesn't create drafts. It just returns one line.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Small, but important. We need to confirm three things first:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Python runs</li>
        <li>The MCP server starts</li>
        <li>Gemini CLI can find this server</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Once this passes, <strong>adding features afterward is much less likely to send you down a rabbit hole.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 4 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 4</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Connect the MCP Server to Gemini CLI</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Now Gemini CLI needs to know where this MCP server lives. In VS Code's file explorer, create a <code>.gemini</code> folder, then create <code>settings.json</code> inside it:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-json">{
  "mcpServers": {
    "course-notes": {
      "command": "uv",
      "args": ["run", "python", "server.py"],
      "cwd": "Replace with the full path to your project folder",
      "timeout": 30000,
      "trust": false,
      "includeTools": ["hello"]
    }
  }
}</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        What this says: in the folder pointed to by <code>cwd</code>, run <code>uv run python server.py</code>. That is, <strong>start the MCP server using uv's project environment</strong>.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        <code>cwd</code> examples:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Windows: <code>"cwd": "C:/Users/your-name/Desktop/my-first-mcp-server"</code></li>
        <li>macOS: <code>"cwd": "/Users/your-name/Desktop/my-first-mcp-server"</code></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">The final layout looks at least like this:</p>

      <pre class="code-block code-block--tree" is:raw><code>my-first-mcp-server/
├─ .gemini/
│  └─ settings.json
├─ server.py
├─ class_notes/
└─ drafts/</code></pre>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Gemini CLI finds MCP servers via the <code>mcpServers</code> entry in <code>settings.json</code>. For stdio, it uses <code>command</code>, <code>args</code>, <code>cwd</code>, and similar fields.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 5 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 5</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Verify the MCP Server Connected</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        With the config in place, start Gemini CLI from VS Code's integrated terminal:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">gemini</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">Once inside Gemini CLI, type:</p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-shell">/mcp list</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If <code>course-notes</code> shows up as connected, ask Gemini to try the tool:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please call the hello tool from course-notes.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">If it replies:</p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Class-notes MCP server is running.
      </blockquote>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          That's the first step done.<br/>
          <strong>The minimal version runs inside Gemini CLI.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Part 2: Add the real tools ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 2</span>
        <span class="part-text">Add the Real Tools</span>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 6 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 6</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Upgrade server.py to the Full Version</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        With <code>hello</code> working, we can start adding tools that do real work. Replace <code>server.py</code> with this version:
      </p>

      <details class="details-card details-card--code">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Full server.py</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand the code</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body details-card__body--flush">
          <pre class="code-block code-block--in-details"><code class="lang-python">{fullServerPy}</code></pre>
        </div>
      </details>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This version does several things:
      </p>

      <ol class="numbered-list">
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text"><code>list_notes</code> lists which notes can be read</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text"><code>read_note</code> reads a specific note</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text"><code>create_reflection_draft</code> creates a new draft</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">4</span><span class="numbered-list__text"><code>course://reflection-rules</code> provides the fixed reflection rules</span></li>
        <li><span class="numbered-list__num">5</span><span class="numbered-list__text"><code>draft_reflection</code> provides a fixed reflection workflow</span></li>
      </ol>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          With this, we're not just shipping a tool —<br/>
          we're shipping a small MCP server with <strong>tools, a resource, and a prompt</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- STEP 7 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 7</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Update Gemini CLI's Allowed-Tools List</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Earlier, <code>settings.json</code> only exposed <code>hello</code>. Now we have more tools, so update <code>includeTools</code> to:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-json">"includeTools": [
  "hello",
  "list_notes",
  "read_note",
  "create_reflection_draft"
]</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        We're keeping <code>includeTools</code>. The reason:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Even if you wrote the MCP server yourself,<br/>
          <strong>don't get into the habit of "expose everything."</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Expose only what's needed right now. When you add riskier tools later (delete a file, modify the originals, hit an external API), this discipline matters even more.
      </p>

      <!-- STEP 8 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 8</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Drop In Two Sample Notes</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For <code>list_notes</code> and <code>read_note</code> to have something to work with, we put two sample notes inside <code>class_notes/</code>.
      </p>

      <details class="details-card details-card--code">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">ai_agent_basics.md sample content</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand (copy as a whole)</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body details-card__body--flush">
          <pre class="code-block code-block--in-details code-block--md"><code class="lang-markdown">{aiAgentBasicsMd}</code></pre>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card details-card--code">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">mcp_tools_resources_prompts.md sample content</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand (copy as a whole)</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body details-card__body--flush">
          <pre class="code-block code-block--in-details code-block--md"><code class="lang-markdown">{mcpPrimitivesMd}</code></pre>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- STEP 9 -->
      <div class="case-header">
        <p class="case-label">STEP 9</p>
        <h2 class="case-title">Run Your First Full Flow</h2>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Test it inside Gemini CLI. Start with:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please list the class notes I currently have.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If it works, Gemini calls <code>list_notes</code> and shows the <code>.md</code> files inside <code>class_notes</code>. Next:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Please read ai_agent_basics.md and pull out three key points.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Now Gemini calls <code>read_note</code>, reads the chosen note, and organizes the content. Then:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Based on ai_agent_basics.md, with "my understanding of MCP" as the topic, please draft a class reflection for me.<br/>
        <strong>Don't create the file yet — show me the draft so I can confirm.</strong>
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The important part: <strong>"Don't create the file yet — show me the draft so I can confirm."</strong> That keeps a human in the loop. The AI can read, organize, and draft; whether to actually write the file should still get a human checkpoint.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Once the draft looks good:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Looks good. Please save it as a reflection draft titled "My Understanding of MCP."
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Now Gemini can call <code>create_reflection_draft</code>.
      </p>

      <!-- ============ Part 3: Boundaries and debugging ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 3</span>
        <span class="part-text">Boundaries and Debugging</span>
      </div>

      <!-- Why creating new files is safer than modifying old ones -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Why Creating New Files Is Safer Than Modifying Old Ones</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        You might wonder: since the AI can already create drafts, why not let it modify the originals directly? Technically, sure — but <strong>not in version one</strong>. Modifying existing files carries more risk.
      </p>

      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>If the AI gets it wrong, you might <strong>lose the original content</strong></li>
        <li>If the AI picks the wrong file, recovery is <strong>hard</strong></li>
        <li>If the student isn't familiar with the flow yet, it's <strong>harder to tell where things broke</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So here we let the AI create new drafts only — never modify the originals.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          The first time you wire up writes,<br/>
          <strong>create new things — don't overwrite old ones.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        That's why we keep originals in <code>class_notes/</code> and outputs in <code>drafts/</code>. <strong>Two folders, one workflow — much easier to follow.</strong>
      </p>

      <!-- Safety boundaries in the code -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Safety Boundaries in the Code</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The program is short, but it already has a few boundaries.
      </p>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">Boundary 1: Block weird paths</h3>
      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">name = Path(filename).name</code></pre>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Stops users from passing things like <code>../secret.txt</code>. We don't want the AI reading anything outside the designated folder.
      </p>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">Boundary 2: .md only</h3>
      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">if path.suffix != ".md":
    raise ValueError("Only .md notes are allowed for now.")</code></pre>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Restricts reads to Markdown notes.
      </p>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">Boundary 3: Don't overwrite</h3>
      <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-python">if path.exists():
    return f"Draft already exists: {filename}. I did not overwrite it. Please use a different title."</code></pre>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If the draft already exists, <strong>don't overwrite it</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          These look small, but together they make the agent <strong>much less likely to go off the rails</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Common errors -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Common Errors</h2>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">1. Gemini CLI can't find my MCP server</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click for the checklist</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Check that <code>settings.json</code> is in the right place. For project-level config, it should live at:
          </p>
          <pre class="code-block code-block--tree" is:raw><code>my-first-mcp-server/.gemini/settings.json</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Then check that <code>cwd</code> points to your actual project folder. <strong>Often the code isn't wrong — Gemini CLI just doesn't know where to launch server.py from.</strong>
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">2. I installed via uv, but Gemini CLI can't find mcp</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click for the checklist</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Make sure <code>settings.json</code> is using the uv version:
          </p>
          <pre class="code-block" is:raw><code class="lang-json">"command": "uv",
"args": ["run", "python", "server.py"]</code></pre>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            That way Gemini CLI launches the server through uv's project environment. Also confirm <code>cwd</code> points to the right folder — uv needs to find the project config there.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">3. Tools show up but fail when called</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click for the checklist</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            First confirm there are actual <code>.md</code> files inside <code>class_notes</code>. You can also try:
          </p>
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Please use the hello tool to confirm the server is running.
          </blockquote>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            If <code>hello</code> works but <code>list_notes</code> fails, <strong>it's usually a folder or file path issue</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">4. The draft wasn't created</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click for the checklist</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Check that the <code>drafts</code> folder exists. The program creates it on demand, but if it lacks permission, it can still fail.
          </p>
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Also check that the title doesn't collide with an existing draft. If it does, the program stops and won't overwrite.
          </p>
          <div class="callout-card">
            <p class="callout-text">
              That's <strong>not a bug</strong> — it's a deliberate safety boundary.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- How this resembles the Claude Code workflow -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">How This Mirrors the Claude Code Workflow</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        We didn't use Claude Code here, but we already practiced a very similar way of working.
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>We <strong>collaborate with the AI in a CLI</strong></li>
        <li>We let the AI <strong>read project data</strong></li>
        <li>We let the AI <strong>call tools based on the task</strong></li>
        <li>We <strong>govern tool boundaries through a config file</strong></li>
        <li>We <strong>break tasks down</strong>, so the AI never does too much at once</li>
        <li>We <strong>preserve human confirmation</strong> instead of letting the AI run free</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So this isn't really about copying any one tool's look. The real lesson is the way of working underneath:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card highlight-card--final">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Bring the AI into your workspace —<br/>
          <strong>but only with the tools and boundaries it actually needs.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
